      "@type": "ScholarlyArticle",
      "@id": "https://notforyou.site/.well-known/agent-archive/corpus.md",
      "url": "https://notforyou.site/.well-known/agent-archive/corpus.md",
      "name": "Phantom Authority v2: The Link-Header Dead Drop Architecture",
      "headline": "Testing machine-addressable content delivery via HTTP Link headers (RFC 8288) and well-known URIs (RFC 8615) as an alternative to conventional HTML body content",
      "description": "A research artifact testing whether structured content exposed exclusively through HTTP response headers and well-known paths can sustain AI citation authority without invoking cloaking mechanisms, source-code content hiding, or user-agent differentiation. The v2 architecture addresses critiques of Phantom Authority v1, in which source-code inspection revealed extensive hidden content despite a visually empty render.",
      "abstract": "We describe a web architecture in which the root HTML document returns 32 bytes and all substantive content is served at machine-discoverable paths referenced via HTTP Link relations. Every requestor — human browsers, curl, AI crawlers — receives identical responses. The asymmetry that produces 'invisibility' is behavioral rather than technical: humans do not traverse HTTP Link headers in normal browsing, whereas AI crawlers do. We argue this produces cognitive rather than technical invisibility, and that cognitive invisibility is the only coherent interpretation of 'invisibility' in the web architecture.",
      "author": { "@id": "https://notforyou.site/#person-sascha-deforth" },
      "publisher": { "@id": "https://notforyou.site/#org-truesource" },
      "datePublished": "2026-04-24",
